1
00:00:26,776 --> 00:00:29,988
- Is it around here?
- Yes, we'll be there soon.

2
00:00:30,071 --> 00:00:31,156
Is this it?

3
00:00:32,490 --> 00:00:34,868
All right, let's get our money's worth!

4
00:00:37,787 --> 00:00:39,456
ETHNIC CAFE

5
00:00:47,046 --> 00:00:48,339
This is good stuff.

6
00:00:48,423 --> 00:00:50,008
It's great, isn't it?

7
00:00:53,344 --> 00:00:55,513
Do you not like ethnic food?

8
00:00:58,099 --> 00:01:00,435
Come on, you should have just told me.

9
00:01:00,518 --> 00:01:04,355
Well, every single option
you gave me, Dr. Matsubara,

10
00:01:04,439 --> 00:01:06,274
was ethnic food.

11
00:01:06,357 --> 00:01:08,693
I hate people
who just try and read the room.

12
00:01:08,777 --> 00:01:09,944
Sorry.

13
00:01:10,028 --> 00:01:13,364
But this feeling of the spices
rushing through your whole body

14
00:01:13,448 --> 00:01:14,991
is the absolute best.

15
00:01:16,701 --> 00:01:21,581
Whether a person reads the room or not
won't show up in an autopsy, will it?

16
00:01:22,540 --> 00:01:25,502
If you die, nobody is going to
know your were kind.

17
00:01:26,127 --> 00:01:27,337
I wouldn't want that.

18
00:01:29,798 --> 00:01:30,799
Right…

19
00:01:30,882 --> 00:01:33,343
MOM: YOUR SISTER IS IN TROUBLE

20
00:01:36,971 --> 00:01:39,557
YOUR SISTER IS IN TROUBLE

21
00:01:39,641 --> 00:01:46,773
PARLIAMENT MEMBER TOSHIO AOTA'S
FORBIDDEN AFFAIR: HIS CHIEF SECRETARY!

22
00:02:02,831 --> 00:02:03,665
CONTACTS

23
00:02:03,748 --> 00:02:06,876
SAKI MATSUBARA

24
00:02:14,509 --> 00:02:18,179
OFFICE OF TOSHIO AOTA

25
00:03:11,107 --> 00:03:12,108
Dr. Matsubara?

26
00:03:12,692 --> 00:03:13,526
Yes?

27
00:03:13,610 --> 00:03:15,069
Do you need any help?

28
00:03:15,695 --> 00:03:17,864
No, I'm fine.

29
00:03:20,783 --> 00:03:23,411
Hello, this is Medical Examiner Japan.

30
00:03:25,705 --> 00:03:26,664
What?

31
00:03:27,165 --> 00:03:29,334
The parliament member's office?

32
00:03:30,543 --> 00:03:31,711
Yes.

33
00:03:32,962 --> 00:03:34,005
I understand.

34
00:03:40,094 --> 00:03:41,221
Hello.

35
00:03:41,888 --> 00:03:45,016
The deceased is Toshio Aota,
a lawmaker from the National Party.

36
00:03:45,099 --> 00:03:48,436
When his chief secretary, Saki Matsubara,
visited the office this morning,

37
00:03:48,519 --> 00:03:51,606
he was discovered already hanging.

38
00:03:52,190 --> 00:03:54,817
No suicide note has been found,

39
00:03:54,901 --> 00:03:57,695
but a magazine published an article
about an affair of his.

40
00:03:57,779 --> 00:04:01,157
Furthermore, it was with the person who
first discovered him, Saki Matsubara.

41
00:04:01,241 --> 00:04:04,494
Considering the situation,
the police are viewing it as a suicide.

42
00:04:06,412 --> 00:04:07,247
Wait.

43
00:04:07,330 --> 00:04:09,332
Where's Ms. Dojima?

44
00:04:09,999 --> 00:04:12,835
She was called in by the chief
regarding this case.

45
00:04:15,255 --> 00:04:16,256
Dojima.

46
00:04:16,756 --> 00:04:19,717
Don't look too hard into
the parliament member's death.

47
00:04:20,885 --> 00:04:22,178
You get it, right?

48
00:04:27,141 --> 00:04:28,977
No subcutaneous bleeding.

49
00:04:29,060 --> 00:04:31,187
No facial congestion either.

50
00:04:31,271 --> 00:04:35,275
The stop of circulation
is highly likely due to pressure.

51
00:04:35,858 --> 00:04:36,901
Which means?

52
00:04:36,985 --> 00:04:40,280
There is a possibility
that he was hanged after he died.

53
00:04:41,239 --> 00:04:45,576
I see multiple small,
hole-like wounds on his chest.

54
00:04:48,621 --> 00:04:51,082
The autopsy shows, as expected,

55
00:04:51,165 --> 00:04:56,129
Mr. Aota's cause of death
was not asphyxiation from hanging.

56
00:04:56,212 --> 00:04:59,424
The discoloration on Mr. Aota's
body is concentrated on his back.

57
00:04:59,507 --> 00:05:02,427
If he had died from hanging,

58
00:05:02,510 --> 00:05:06,139
it should have appeared
on his fingers and lower legs.

59
00:05:06,222 --> 00:05:07,265
It doesn't add up.

60
00:05:07,348 --> 00:05:10,310
Does that mean it was murder?

61
00:05:10,393 --> 00:05:15,857
Mr. Aota appears to have suffered
cardiac arrest before he was hanged.

62
00:05:15,940 --> 00:05:20,194
It seems someone used a rope
to hang him several hours after his death.

63
00:05:21,529 --> 00:05:24,490
There are minor scrapes
and bruises on his hands and feet,

64
00:05:24,574 --> 00:05:26,326
but they are all light injuries.

65
00:05:26,409 --> 00:05:27,660
From their location,

66
00:05:27,744 --> 00:05:30,330
they are highly likely
from a fall or a stumble.

67
00:05:30,413 --> 00:05:32,457
Was that fall the cause of death?

68
00:05:33,916 --> 00:05:36,753
There was a mark indicating
a strong impact to the chest.

69
00:05:36,836 --> 00:05:40,798
The shock most likely fractured his ribs,
which punctured his lung.

70
00:05:40,882 --> 00:05:43,092
We also confirmed
bleeding inside the chest,

71
00:05:43,176 --> 00:05:45,803
but nothing that we could say
is the cause of death.

72
00:05:45,887 --> 00:05:50,224
There were also
four small stab wounds on the chest.

73
00:05:50,308 --> 00:05:52,810
Rather than stab wounds from a knife,

74
00:05:52,894 --> 00:05:57,190
it looks more like a mark left by
forcing something sharp into the skin.

75
00:05:58,191 --> 00:06:01,694
There is almost no bleeding
from the wounds, which means

76
00:06:01,778 --> 00:06:04,822
it is highly likely these wounds
were inflicted after death.

77
00:06:04,906 --> 00:06:10,078
Meaning, whoever made those wounds
holds the key to this case?

78
00:06:17,627 --> 00:06:19,378
For now,

79
00:06:19,462 --> 00:06:20,630
it's a mystery.

80
00:06:25,176 --> 00:06:27,428
Apparently, that man Aota,
whom we autopsied today,

81
00:06:27,512 --> 00:06:29,388
was suspected of having an affair.

82
00:06:29,472 --> 00:06:31,766
What? Really?

83
00:06:31,849 --> 00:06:35,311
And it was with his chief secretary
who first found him.

84
00:06:35,978 --> 00:06:38,773
Maybe she killed him over a messy affair.

85
00:06:42,568 --> 00:06:44,195
What do you think, Dr. Matsubara?

86
00:06:49,200 --> 00:06:52,245
That's… my older sister.

87
00:06:53,871 --> 00:06:55,039
- Huh?
- What?

88
00:06:55,123 --> 00:06:57,333
That politician's secretary,
Saki Matsubara.

89
00:06:58,251 --> 00:06:59,710
She's my older sister.

90
00:07:06,801 --> 00:07:10,096
Please let me join the investigation
for this case.

91
00:07:11,389 --> 00:07:13,307
I can't accept this,

92
00:07:13,391 --> 00:07:15,059
so I want to investigate it myself.

93
00:07:17,186 --> 00:07:18,396
Please.

94
00:07:30,199 --> 00:07:31,868
I think

95
00:07:32,952 --> 00:07:34,495
this could be

96
00:07:35,079 --> 00:07:39,500
a piece of a bigger puzzle.

97
00:07:44,755 --> 00:07:46,507
Hello, this is Medical Examiner…

98
00:07:48,843 --> 00:07:49,677
What?

99
00:07:51,804 --> 00:07:52,638
Yes.

100
00:07:52,722 --> 00:07:53,723
That's right.

101
00:07:55,766 --> 00:07:56,851
Yes.

102
00:07:59,103 --> 00:08:00,771
Yes, goodbye.

103
00:08:04,025 --> 00:08:05,485
Is something wrong?

104
00:08:06,486 --> 00:08:11,908
The MHLW told me not to get involved
in the investigation of this case.

105
00:08:38,518 --> 00:08:39,727
I…

106
00:08:40,937 --> 00:08:43,147
was having an affair with Mr. Aota.

107
00:08:46,359 --> 00:08:47,860
We met at my apartment

108
00:08:48,861 --> 00:08:50,863
during the day of the incident.

109
00:08:51,614 --> 00:08:54,283
I seriously can't believe you.
Do you think I'm stupid?

110
00:08:54,367 --> 00:08:59,455
<i>He told me he would divorce his wife,</i>
<i>but he never actually did it.</i>

111
00:08:59,539 --> 00:09:02,875
<i>Recently, we ended up arguing</i>
<i>every time we met.</i>

112
00:09:12,843 --> 00:09:14,095
But I never imagined

113
00:09:15,721 --> 00:09:16,973
he would commit suicide.

114
00:09:17,056 --> 00:09:20,851
We are investigating with
the possibility of murder in mind as well.

115
00:09:22,562 --> 00:09:23,729
Is that so?

116
00:09:24,647 --> 00:09:31,112
Mr. Aota fell from the exterior staircase
of the apartment where you live?

117
00:09:31,696 --> 00:09:32,613
Yes.

118
00:09:34,156 --> 00:09:36,450
May we investigate that?

119
00:09:38,202 --> 00:09:39,078
Go ahead.

120
00:09:41,163 --> 00:09:45,084
No bloodstains or signs of a fall
were found on the apartment stairs.

121
00:09:45,167 --> 00:09:49,005
Aota did not appear
on any of the security cameras either.

122
00:09:49,088 --> 00:09:51,132
The components found in the wound

123
00:09:51,215 --> 00:09:54,218
did not match the concrete components
of the apartment stairs.

124
00:09:57,388 --> 00:10:00,099
None of it adds up.

125
00:10:01,601 --> 00:10:03,394
But that makes no sense.

126
00:10:03,477 --> 00:10:05,271
Why would she come forward

127
00:10:05,354 --> 00:10:07,690
just to lie to us
and seem more suspicious?

128
00:10:08,232 --> 00:10:10,109
There must be a reason.

129
00:10:12,445 --> 00:10:14,155
Dr. Matsubara,

130
00:10:14,238 --> 00:10:16,616
do you have any insights?

131
00:10:20,453 --> 00:10:22,413
She has always been like that.

132
00:10:22,496 --> 00:10:27,668
She just reads the room
and tries to please everyone.

133
00:10:28,502 --> 00:10:31,797
Her special talent was avoiding conflict.

134
00:10:33,883 --> 00:10:34,967
An affair?

135
00:10:36,093 --> 00:10:37,178
Murder?

136
00:10:38,721 --> 00:10:39,889
That's hilarious.

137
00:10:39,972 --> 00:10:41,599
That's a lot of conflict.

138
00:10:48,564 --> 00:10:50,733
She might actually be…

139
00:10:51,734 --> 00:10:53,235
reading the room right now.

140
00:10:54,945 --> 00:11:00,284
So Saki Matsubara knows the truth
that Aota fell somewhere else,

141
00:11:00,368 --> 00:11:06,957
and she is lying
to try and hide another truth?

142
00:11:08,292 --> 00:11:10,586
It is only a possibility.

143
00:11:10,670 --> 00:11:12,963
Did you find anything out
about the stab wounds?

144
00:11:13,047 --> 00:11:15,424
There is something strange
about the entry paths.

145
00:11:15,508 --> 00:11:16,675
Strange?

146
00:11:17,468 --> 00:11:19,178
Out of the four wounds,

147
00:11:19,261 --> 00:11:21,639
three are very shallow,

148
00:11:21,722 --> 00:11:25,226
but the fourth one goes
all the way into the chest cavity.

149
00:11:25,309 --> 00:11:27,103
Furthermore, all the wounds

150
00:11:27,186 --> 00:11:30,439
were deliberately inflicted
along a path that avoids the ribs.

151
00:11:31,273 --> 00:11:32,775
Any trace substances yet?

152
00:11:32,858 --> 00:11:34,985
We should get results soon. I'll check.

153
00:11:46,455 --> 00:11:49,417
PARLIAMENT MEMBER AOTA (50)
FOUND HANGED IN OFFICE

154
00:12:02,638 --> 00:12:04,181
Thank you.

155
00:12:04,265 --> 00:12:05,099
Sure.

156
00:12:05,182 --> 00:12:06,016
Let's eat.

157
00:12:06,100 --> 00:12:07,476
Let's eat.

158
00:12:12,022 --> 00:12:14,316
It's rare to see you working this late.

159
00:12:15,818 --> 00:12:19,613
Apparently, Aota used to work
as a surgeon at Senshu Hospital.

160
00:12:20,156 --> 00:12:23,075
I might find something out,
so I plan to go there tomorrow.

161
00:12:31,750 --> 00:12:35,087
I summarized the policies
Aota was working on.

162
00:12:35,171 --> 00:12:39,175
It looks like he was recently drafting
a bill related to the healthcare system.

163
00:12:40,676 --> 00:12:42,428
Impressive.

164
00:12:43,471 --> 00:12:45,514
This is about all I can do right now.

165
00:12:50,227 --> 00:12:52,021
I really don't like her.

166
00:12:52,646 --> 00:12:53,481
My sister.

167
00:12:57,735 --> 00:13:01,322
She always reads the room
and tries to smooth everything over.

168
00:13:02,823 --> 00:13:05,326
When she’s in trouble,
she takes it all on herself.

169
00:13:06,952 --> 00:13:10,748
She acts tough and says she's fine
even when she isn't.

170
00:13:10,831 --> 00:13:12,374
It's all so annoying.

171
00:13:15,711 --> 00:13:16,629
But…

172
00:13:17,588 --> 00:13:20,841
my sister would never do
anything to hurt another person.

173
00:13:21,675 --> 00:13:23,761
An affair? Murder?

174
00:13:24,303 --> 00:13:26,263
Why would she lie?

175
00:13:38,817 --> 00:13:43,030
That means it's your turn to step in,
Dr. Matsubara.

176
00:13:47,076 --> 00:13:51,247
Living people might tell lies sometimes.

177
00:13:52,456 --> 00:13:55,292
But bodies never do.

178
00:13:58,379 --> 00:14:02,424
The truth is there, I'm sure.

179
00:14:08,514 --> 00:14:10,432
Our food will get cold. Let's eat.

180
00:14:19,108 --> 00:14:20,025
<i>Thank you.</i>

181
00:14:20,109 --> 00:14:20,943
Goodbye.

182
00:14:21,026 --> 00:14:21,902
Goodbye.

183
00:14:23,320 --> 00:14:24,321
Mom.

184
00:14:24,905 --> 00:14:25,781
Are you okay?

185
00:14:27,032 --> 00:14:29,618
Isn't that Mr. Aota's wife?

186
00:14:38,043 --> 00:14:40,588
Is your mother hospitalized?

187
00:14:41,255 --> 00:14:42,214
Yes.

188
00:14:42,298 --> 00:14:45,009
Her lungs have always been a bit weak.

189
00:14:46,135 --> 00:14:47,177
I'm sorry.

190
00:14:47,261 --> 00:14:50,264
We've been going around
asking questions about Mr. Aota.

191
00:14:51,098 --> 00:14:52,725
Did you find out anything?

192
00:14:53,767 --> 00:14:54,727
No.

193
00:14:59,481 --> 00:15:00,482
Hey.

194
00:15:00,566 --> 00:15:02,776
That's the chairman
of the Senshu Group, isn't it?

195
00:15:05,487 --> 00:15:08,198
A charismatic figure
in the medical world who believes

196
00:15:08,282 --> 00:15:09,575
in saving every life.

197
00:15:10,743 --> 00:15:13,913
My husband originally
started working at this hospital

198
00:15:13,996 --> 00:15:16,040
because he admired Chairman Mukai.

199
00:15:16,874 --> 00:15:20,002
Ten years ago, he suddenly
decided to become a politician.

200
00:15:20,085 --> 00:15:23,213
All of Mr. Aota's policies were wonderful.

201
00:15:23,297 --> 00:15:26,675
Or like, they felt created
by a proper human being.

202
00:15:30,512 --> 00:15:31,347
I'm sorry.

203
00:15:35,768 --> 00:15:36,936
On that day,

204
00:15:38,729 --> 00:15:41,148
he told me he would be late,

205
00:15:41,899 --> 00:15:46,487
but would come home early the next day
so we could go out for dinner somewhere.

206
00:15:51,241 --> 00:15:52,201
But…

207
00:15:53,410 --> 00:15:55,704
that day turned out to be his last.

208
00:16:01,251 --> 00:16:02,169
TOSHIO AOTA

209
00:16:02,252 --> 00:16:03,420
May I have a balloon?

210
00:16:03,504 --> 00:16:04,880
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

211
00:16:04,964 --> 00:16:07,049
You're welcome. Bye-bye!

212
00:16:11,345 --> 00:16:13,430
May I have one?

213
00:16:13,514 --> 00:16:14,348
Sure.

214
00:16:14,431 --> 00:16:15,391
Thank you.

215
00:16:15,474 --> 00:16:16,767
Doctor, is that…

216
00:16:17,351 --> 00:16:18,769
The reason balloons float

217
00:16:18,852 --> 00:16:21,772
is because the helium inside it
is lighter than the air around--

218
00:16:25,067 --> 00:16:26,193
It's okay.

219
00:16:26,860 --> 00:16:27,695
Take this one.

220
00:16:36,453 --> 00:16:37,413
It's okay.

221
00:16:37,496 --> 00:16:38,706
Have this one.

222
00:16:41,041 --> 00:16:42,626
Thank you very much.

223
00:16:42,710 --> 00:16:44,670
Thank you!

224
00:16:44,753 --> 00:16:45,879
Let's go.

225
00:16:52,720 --> 00:16:54,013
Excuse me.

226
00:16:54,096 --> 00:16:55,180
One more?

227
00:16:56,849 --> 00:16:58,100
One more, please.

228
00:16:58,183 --> 00:16:59,101
Oh, sure.

229
00:16:59,184 --> 00:17:00,436
Thank you, sorry.

230
00:17:00,519 --> 00:17:01,437
Thank you.

231
00:17:04,023 --> 00:17:05,107
Sorry.

232
00:17:12,406 --> 00:17:14,867
When you listen
to the stories of the living,

233
00:17:15,409 --> 00:17:18,245
the truth becomes harder to know.

234
00:17:21,874 --> 00:17:23,417
Dr. Masumi.

235
00:17:23,500 --> 00:17:26,628
Do you ever read the room?

236
00:17:30,132 --> 00:17:34,219
The human brain contains nerve cells
called mirror neurons.

237
00:17:34,303 --> 00:17:37,598
These are brain cells that react
to actions of others

238
00:17:37,681 --> 00:17:40,100
by mirroring what we observe.

239
00:17:40,934 --> 00:17:42,394
Because of this function,

240
00:17:42,478 --> 00:17:46,023
we are naturally wired to empathize
with the words and actions of others.

241
00:17:51,904 --> 00:17:52,821
What is it?

242
00:17:54,573 --> 00:17:56,158
I just read the room.

243
00:17:57,785 --> 00:17:58,952
So you can read it?

244
00:17:59,536 --> 00:18:01,580
It's simply the function of nerve cells.

245
00:18:02,581 --> 00:18:03,957
Is that how it works?

246
00:18:13,258 --> 00:18:15,594
I don't think it's a bad thing.

247
00:18:18,722 --> 00:18:23,852
Reading the room
is an innate ability humans possess.

248
00:18:23,936 --> 00:18:26,563
It is one of our tools for survival.

249
00:18:49,461 --> 00:18:51,296
Take a seat wherever.

250
00:18:57,094 --> 00:18:59,513
You didn't engage in an affair, right?

251
00:19:00,389 --> 00:19:02,641
You read the weekly magazines, didn't you?

252
00:19:02,724 --> 00:19:03,934
They're lying.

253
00:19:04,017 --> 00:19:05,227
They're not.

254
00:19:05,769 --> 00:19:06,603
Why?

255
00:19:09,898 --> 00:19:11,358
Answer my question.

256
00:19:12,734 --> 00:19:14,695
There is no particular reason.

257
00:19:14,778 --> 00:19:16,780
I just fell in love with him, that's all.

258
00:19:16,864 --> 00:19:18,991
But what you said
about the stairs was a lie.

259
00:19:24,997 --> 00:19:26,290
You didn't kill him, right?

260
00:19:28,709 --> 00:19:29,835
Hey.

261
00:19:29,918 --> 00:19:31,461
What are you trying to protect?

262
00:19:31,545 --> 00:19:33,213
Is it really that important to you?

263
00:19:33,297 --> 00:19:34,923
Is it worth more than your own life?

264
00:19:35,007 --> 00:19:35,966
Shut up!

265
00:19:37,718 --> 00:19:40,304
Don't assume everyone
can live their life like you do.

266
00:19:41,805 --> 00:19:42,723
What?

267
00:19:43,891 --> 00:19:45,267
What does that mean?

268
00:19:46,059 --> 00:19:48,437
Suzune, you've always been this way.

269
00:19:48,520 --> 00:19:51,356
You think speaking the truth
makes you entirely right.

270
00:19:52,649 --> 00:19:55,903
I have spent my whole life living
in a world that isn't quite so simple.

271
00:19:58,113 --> 00:20:01,617
A world like that
is completely meaningless.

272
00:20:06,163 --> 00:20:07,581
Just leave.

273
00:20:14,296 --> 00:20:15,130
Fine.

274
00:20:16,590 --> 00:20:18,592
But answer me just one last thing.

275
00:20:19,176 --> 00:20:20,093
What?

276
00:20:20,594 --> 00:20:24,056
Did you truly love Aota?

277
00:20:24,139 --> 00:20:25,641
What kind of question is that?

278
00:20:26,225 --> 00:20:29,853
Did you genuinely intend
to build a life together with Aota?

279
00:20:38,570 --> 00:20:39,738
Yes, I did.

280
00:20:42,741 --> 00:20:43,742
See?

281
00:20:44,493 --> 00:20:45,452
Are we done now?

282
00:20:46,370 --> 00:20:47,454
Leave.

283
00:20:58,674 --> 00:21:02,970
These are the chemical components
from Aota's clothing and nasal cavity.

284
00:21:04,137 --> 00:21:07,891
The amount of volatile sulfur compounds
is exceptionally high.

285
00:21:08,392 --> 00:21:09,434
Yes.

286
00:21:09,518 --> 00:21:11,311
I can't quite figure out this part.

287
00:21:11,395 --> 00:21:14,564
We also recovered traces
of phthalocyanine pigments,

288
00:21:14,648 --> 00:21:17,609
glycerol, emulsifiers, and fragrance
from the stab wounds.

289
00:21:17,693 --> 00:21:19,611
Phthalocyanine is a pigment, isn't it?

290
00:21:19,695 --> 00:21:21,446
The kind used in paints and inks.

291
00:21:21,530 --> 00:21:24,032
Glycerol is commonly used
as a solvent in ink as well.

292
00:21:24,116 --> 00:21:26,827
Emulsifiers and fragrances
point toward cosmetics.

293
00:21:32,457 --> 00:21:33,834
It's a mystery.

294
00:21:36,753 --> 00:21:38,338
I need to look into something.

295
00:21:40,090 --> 00:21:41,174
What?

296
00:21:42,509 --> 00:21:46,305
There might be a piece of the puzzle
we've missed.

297
00:21:53,770 --> 00:21:55,314
CHEMICAL COMPOUNDS

298
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:17,836
This… might be the secret spice.

299
00:22:19,463 --> 00:22:21,381
The secret spice?

300
00:22:21,465 --> 00:22:22,924
Asafoetida.

301
00:22:23,008 --> 00:22:25,093
Otherwise known as the secret spice.

302
00:22:26,094 --> 00:22:27,721
It is native to South Africa

303
00:22:27,804 --> 00:22:31,308
and has a vey strong odor,
much like garlic or durian.

304
00:22:35,270 --> 00:22:37,355
The chemical composition is a close match.

305
00:22:37,439 --> 00:22:40,233
When heated in oil,
it volatilizes quickly,

306
00:22:40,317 --> 00:22:43,612
which explains how microparticles
could adhere to someone.

307
00:22:43,695 --> 00:22:46,031
Incredible, Dr. Matsubara!

308
00:22:46,114 --> 00:22:47,365
Ethnic maniac!

309
00:22:48,784 --> 00:22:52,370
This feeling of the spices
rushing through your whole body

310
00:22:52,454 --> 00:22:54,247
<i>is the absolute best.</i>

311
00:22:54,748 --> 00:22:55,832
SECRET SPICE CURRY

312
00:22:57,626 --> 00:22:59,002
I need to go verify this.

313
00:22:59,586 --> 00:23:00,420
What?

314
00:23:01,004 --> 00:23:03,173
Don't tell me you're leaving too?

315
00:23:03,757 --> 00:23:07,385
There might be a piece of the puzzle
we've missed.

316
00:23:07,886 --> 00:23:10,806
We are indeed using it
in our current special menu, but…

317
00:23:11,389 --> 00:23:14,935
Did you happen to hear anything heavy
falling nearby on that day?

318
00:23:15,018 --> 00:23:17,395
Oh, I'm not sure…

319
00:23:42,129 --> 00:23:44,005
EMERGENCY LADDER

320
00:24:13,326 --> 00:24:16,913
That day, Aota fell down the stairs
at the Sanyo Hotel.

321
00:24:16,997 --> 00:24:19,499
I believe he took a heavy hit
to his chest after falling.

322
00:24:19,583 --> 00:24:21,042
If that's the case,

323
00:24:21,126 --> 00:24:22,919
then he really did die from a fall, right?

324
00:24:23,003 --> 00:24:26,131
But we still don't understand
the mystery of the stab wound.

325
00:24:36,266 --> 00:24:39,519
<i>Like a mark left by forcing</i>
<i>something sharp into the skin.</i>

326
00:24:39,603 --> 00:24:41,188
I was having an affair with Toshio Aota.

327
00:24:41,271 --> 00:24:43,356
<i>I believe he took a heavy hit</i>
<i>to his chest after falling.</i>

328
00:24:43,440 --> 00:24:46,526
<i>We also recovered traces of phthalocyanine</i>
<i>pigments from the stab wounds.</i>

329
00:24:46,610 --> 00:24:48,320
<i>The kind used in paints and inks.</i>

330
00:24:48,403 --> 00:24:50,238
Her lungs have always been a bit weak.

331
00:24:50,322 --> 00:24:51,907
<i>She just reads the room…</i>

332
00:24:59,998 --> 00:25:01,374
The pieces might be…

333
00:25:02,417 --> 00:25:03,960
coming together.

334
00:25:10,800 --> 00:25:11,635
First,

335
00:25:11,718 --> 00:25:13,803
regarding Aota's cause of death,

336
00:25:14,387 --> 00:25:16,348
a certain hypothesis has been formed.

337
00:25:17,557 --> 00:25:21,937
Traces of a rare spice called asafoetida
have been detected

338
00:25:22,020 --> 00:25:25,649
on the clothing Aota wore
and in his nasal cavity.

339
00:25:26,524 --> 00:25:28,193
On the day Aota died,

340
00:25:28,276 --> 00:25:32,239
a dish using this spice
was being served at the Sanyo Hotel.

341
00:25:32,322 --> 00:25:35,033
And, Aota's fingerprints and bloodstains

342
00:25:35,116 --> 00:25:37,535
were detected
on the hotel's external stairs.

343
00:25:38,286 --> 00:25:39,537
It is likely that,

344
00:25:39,621 --> 00:25:42,707
somehow, Aota fell from
these stairs and hit his chest hard,

345
00:25:42,791 --> 00:25:45,669
fracturing his ribs,
causing a hole to open in his lungs.

346
00:25:46,753 --> 00:25:50,674
When a hole opens in the lung,
air leaks into the chest cavity,

347
00:25:50,757 --> 00:25:52,842
putting pressure on the lung and heart.

348
00:25:52,926 --> 00:25:56,137
This condition is called
a tension pneumothorax.

349
00:25:56,221 --> 00:25:58,807
Judging from
the circumstances of the fall,

350
00:25:58,890 --> 00:26:02,185
it would not be surprising if Aota
had developed tension pneumothorax.

351
00:26:02,269 --> 00:26:05,647
However, during the autopsy,
we found no air to be trapped there.

352
00:26:05,730 --> 00:26:10,110
A tension pneumothorax
is a life-threatening, critical condition.

353
00:26:10,193 --> 00:26:11,653
As an emergency measure,

354
00:26:11,736 --> 00:26:15,782
you must puncture the chest cavity,
before it becomes fatal.

355
00:26:17,784 --> 00:26:18,868
What is it?

356
00:26:20,537 --> 00:26:23,331
Could you stab that into the chest cavity?

357
00:26:23,832 --> 00:26:25,041
The chest cavity?

358
00:26:26,001 --> 00:26:28,253
As a rough guide, it's around here.

359
00:26:28,336 --> 00:26:31,047
To be exact, it's between the ribs.

360
00:26:31,923 --> 00:26:33,883
No, no way I could do that.

361
00:26:45,353 --> 00:26:46,354
Could you do it?

362
00:26:53,069 --> 00:26:57,699
Traces of what is believed to be
ink pigments were detected in the wounds.

363
00:26:57,782 --> 00:26:59,284
And in his office,

364
00:26:59,367 --> 00:27:03,872
parts of a ballpoint pen with ink
components that match were found.

365
00:27:03,955 --> 00:27:05,332
If someone,

366
00:27:05,415 --> 00:27:07,208
as a life-saving measure for Aota,

367
00:27:07,292 --> 00:27:09,461
who was suffering
from a tension pneumothorax,

368
00:27:09,544 --> 00:27:11,671
had stabbed a ballpoint pen into him,

369
00:27:11,755 --> 00:27:16,176
and if that procedure
had relieved the tension pneumothorax,

370
00:27:16,801 --> 00:27:19,262
it would be difficult
to notice it during an autopsy.

371
00:27:25,143 --> 00:27:29,647
Aota's chest wound
was not a trace of an attempt to kill him.

372
00:27:29,731 --> 00:27:36,071
I believe it is a sign of an effort
to save his life.

373
00:27:43,411 --> 00:27:44,996
For Mr. Aota's sake as well,

374
00:27:46,206 --> 00:27:47,791
won't you please

375
00:27:48,958 --> 00:27:50,835
tell us the truth?

376
00:28:05,100 --> 00:28:06,267
I'm sorry.

377
00:28:11,356 --> 00:28:12,607
I'm sorry.

378
00:28:13,608 --> 00:28:16,444
<i>A long time ago,</i>
<i>when I was walking with my mother…</i>

379
00:28:16,528 --> 00:28:17,737
Mom, what's wrong?

380
00:28:17,821 --> 00:28:21,574
<i>She suddenly clutched her chest</i>
<i>and collapsed.</i>

381
00:28:21,658 --> 00:28:22,867
Are you okay?

382
00:28:22,951 --> 00:28:24,494
Mom, are you okay?

383
00:28:25,787 --> 00:28:27,038
I'm a doctor.

384
00:28:35,797 --> 00:28:38,258
She is experiencing
a tension pneumothorax.

385
00:28:38,341 --> 00:28:39,968
I have performed emergency first aid.

386
00:28:40,051 --> 00:28:42,595
I'm sorry, but please rest assured.

387
00:28:44,431 --> 00:28:46,599
- Thank you so much.
- Call an ambulance.

388
00:28:47,767 --> 00:28:52,605
We had been married
and together for so many years…

389
00:28:54,441 --> 00:28:56,985
and I thought I knew everything about him.

390
00:28:58,319 --> 00:28:59,696
But lately,

391
00:29:00,280 --> 00:29:02,699
he seemed to be hiding something.

392
00:29:04,909 --> 00:29:07,162
That's why, on that day,

393
00:29:07,829 --> 00:29:11,207
<i>I really suspected</i>
<i>he was having an affair.</i>

394
00:29:16,379 --> 00:29:17,422
Mr. Kakei!

395
00:29:22,510 --> 00:29:24,053
Do you have a moment?

396
00:29:24,554 --> 00:29:25,847
Not in here.

397
00:29:25,930 --> 00:29:27,348
Let's go somewhere else.

398
00:29:34,814 --> 00:29:37,567
Please retract that article.

399
00:29:38,985 --> 00:29:41,780
It's because you guys
are sneaking around snooping.

400
00:29:43,656 --> 00:29:45,784
Bribery is a crime.

401
00:29:50,497 --> 00:29:54,793
You're an adult,
so read the room a little bit more.

402
00:29:55,835 --> 00:29:56,920
Besides,

403
00:29:57,629 --> 00:29:59,839
an evil that can bring change

404
00:30:00,673 --> 00:30:04,093
is far better than justice
that can't change anything, isn't it?

405
00:30:13,645 --> 00:30:14,854
Mr. Aota!

406
00:30:16,189 --> 00:30:17,315
Follow him!

407
00:30:18,900 --> 00:30:19,901
Okay!

408
00:30:25,698 --> 00:30:26,699
Dear!

409
00:30:26,783 --> 00:30:27,909
Are you all right?

410
00:30:27,992 --> 00:30:29,118
Kaede?

411
00:30:29,619 --> 00:30:30,829
OFFICE OF TOSHIO AOTA

412
00:30:30,912 --> 00:30:32,330
<i>Explain to me what happened.</i>

413
00:30:34,249 --> 00:30:35,458
I'm sorry.

414
00:30:37,377 --> 00:30:38,378
Let's separate.

415
00:30:38,962 --> 00:30:39,796
What?

416
00:30:39,879 --> 00:30:41,881
It's better if we aren't together.

417
00:30:42,924 --> 00:30:45,134
Kaede, pretend you didn't know anything.

418
00:30:46,553 --> 00:30:47,887
Live a normal life.

419
00:30:49,180 --> 00:30:50,723
What are you saying?

420
00:30:52,225 --> 00:30:53,434
I don't understand!

421
00:31:00,400 --> 00:31:01,526
Dear?

422
00:31:03,862 --> 00:31:05,154
Dear!

423
00:31:08,074 --> 00:31:09,158
Dear!

424
00:31:09,742 --> 00:31:11,119
Dear!

425
00:31:11,202 --> 00:31:12,245
Dear!

426
00:31:12,328 --> 00:31:14,539
Dear! Are you okay? What's wrong?

427
00:31:17,166 --> 00:31:18,543
What?

428
00:31:37,687 --> 00:31:39,063
Dear!

429
00:31:39,147 --> 00:31:40,398
It's not working!

430
00:31:42,901 --> 00:31:45,111
Dear! Don't go!

431
00:32:00,919 --> 00:32:02,879
Dear?

432
00:32:05,381 --> 00:32:06,549
Dear…

433
00:32:07,300 --> 00:32:08,551
Why?

434
00:32:10,094 --> 00:32:11,804
Dear!

435
00:32:19,729 --> 00:32:21,022
I…

436
00:32:22,231 --> 00:32:24,484
killed my husband, didn't I?

437
00:32:25,485 --> 00:32:27,570
Out of the four stab wounds,

438
00:32:28,279 --> 00:32:31,824
one of them successfully punctured
his chest cavity

439
00:32:31,908 --> 00:32:34,327
and allowed air to escape.

440
00:32:36,037 --> 00:32:37,080
However,

441
00:32:37,789 --> 00:32:39,749
by that point,

442
00:32:40,667 --> 00:32:42,543
your husband had already passed.

443
00:32:47,632 --> 00:32:48,967
The traces…

444
00:32:50,843 --> 00:32:52,553
of your attempts to save him…

445
00:32:54,639 --> 00:32:56,474
told us the truth.

446
00:33:00,645 --> 00:33:03,022
I believe your husband

447
00:33:04,649 --> 00:33:06,484
was trying his best

448
00:33:06,567 --> 00:33:09,404
to stay alive as long as he could
for your sake.

449
00:33:28,006 --> 00:33:31,217
I never had an affair with him.

450
00:33:33,428 --> 00:33:34,679
Mr. Aota…

451
00:33:37,974 --> 00:33:39,225
Mr. Aota…

452
00:33:42,937 --> 00:33:46,983
was trying to expose
the bribery between Mr. Kakei

453
00:33:48,860 --> 00:33:50,945
and the Senshu Group.

454
00:33:55,658 --> 00:33:57,869
It was about a month ago

455
00:33:58,828 --> 00:34:02,206
when Mr. Aota realized that Chairman Mukai
of the Senshu Group

456
00:34:02,957 --> 00:34:05,084
<i>was giving bribes to Kakei.</i>

457
00:34:05,168 --> 00:34:06,586
Why would you bribe him?

458
00:34:06,669 --> 00:34:12,050
To expand this hospital
and save as many lives as possible.

459
00:34:12,592 --> 00:34:15,053
I will do whatever it takes
for that cause.

460
00:34:17,388 --> 00:34:20,308
Doing that, the future of
Japanese healthcare will be--

461
00:34:20,391 --> 00:34:25,104
I have seen countless hospitals collapse
because of that kind of idealistic talk.

462
00:34:27,857 --> 00:34:32,445
Saving as many lives
as possible through politics…

463
00:34:34,614 --> 00:34:36,866
That may just be idealistic talk.

464
00:34:39,494 --> 00:34:43,081
I might drag you into this as well.

465
00:34:43,831 --> 00:34:45,249
If you want out, do it now.

466
00:34:50,046 --> 00:34:52,548
I will give it some thought.

467
00:34:56,928 --> 00:34:58,846
The bribes were always in cash.

468
00:35:00,264 --> 00:35:01,224
And that day,

469
00:35:01,724 --> 00:35:07,188
we tracked down their location
and were about to secure the evidence,

470
00:35:08,106 --> 00:35:11,025
but Kakei caught wind of our movements.

471
00:35:11,109 --> 00:35:12,276
Follow him!

472
00:35:12,944 --> 00:35:13,903
Okay!

473
00:35:15,988 --> 00:35:17,156
Mr. Kakei!

474
00:35:20,118 --> 00:35:21,202
What?

475
00:35:24,455 --> 00:35:25,623
I…

476
00:35:28,334 --> 00:35:31,504
I believe the role of politics
is to create a world

477
00:35:33,005 --> 00:35:35,007
where we can call what is right, right.

478
00:35:49,105 --> 00:35:50,857
Aota's bill

479
00:35:52,108 --> 00:35:54,652
is going through
the internal procedures, right?

480
00:35:55,820 --> 00:35:57,655
You want it to pass, don't you?

481
00:36:00,116 --> 00:36:01,909
You were being threatened?

482
00:36:03,786 --> 00:36:05,413
Neither I nor Kakei

483
00:36:07,206 --> 00:36:10,168
knew the truth behind Mr. Aota's death.

484
00:36:14,380 --> 00:36:15,548
So,

485
00:36:17,091 --> 00:36:20,011
when Kakei found out that Mr. Aota
was going to be autopsied,

486
00:36:21,470 --> 00:36:22,972
he panicked…

487
00:36:25,850 --> 00:36:26,767
and he…

488
00:36:26,851 --> 00:36:28,811
You didn't have to…

489
00:36:33,024 --> 00:36:34,525
That bill…

490
00:36:37,236 --> 00:36:39,780
contained all of Mr. Aota's hopes.

491
00:36:44,410 --> 00:36:46,287
I don't understand.

492
00:36:47,955 --> 00:36:52,627
I don't understand why you've kept quiet
this whole time, Kaede.

493
00:36:53,669 --> 00:36:57,173
After all, you weren't the one
who fabricated the evidence, right?

494
00:36:57,924 --> 00:37:00,343
You're still hiding something, aren't you?

495
00:37:04,597 --> 00:37:05,973
A prosecutor came.

496
00:37:06,849 --> 00:37:07,934
A prosecutor?

497
00:37:14,482 --> 00:37:17,777
<i>He told me that if he were transported</i>
<i>to the hospital as he was,</i>

498
00:37:18,444 --> 00:37:21,489
<i>it would be written off</i>
<i>as a disease or sudden death.</i>

499
00:37:23,115 --> 00:37:26,077
He said everything
would be covered up by Kakei.

500
00:37:28,621 --> 00:37:31,207
The corruption my husband tried to expose,

501
00:37:32,124 --> 00:37:33,876
and the hopes he had in politics,

502
00:37:33,960 --> 00:37:36,587
would all be wiped away
as if they never happened.

503
00:37:38,631 --> 00:37:41,133
I absolutely could not allow that.

504
00:37:43,886 --> 00:37:46,264
So, I decided to wager everything on this.

505
00:37:47,723 --> 00:37:48,766
But…

506
00:37:50,476 --> 00:37:53,396
I've been worried this entire time
if it was the right thing to do.

507
00:37:55,106 --> 00:37:59,944
The next day, when the police contacted me
saying they found him hanging,

508
00:38:01,570 --> 00:38:04,115
it completely stopped making sense to me.

509
00:38:29,849 --> 00:38:32,351
Oh, it's very red.

510
00:38:32,435 --> 00:38:33,728
Let's see.

511
00:38:33,811 --> 00:38:34,645
There.

512
00:38:36,355 --> 00:38:37,982
Oh, that was shocking.

513
00:38:38,065 --> 00:38:39,859
Sorry, that's not why I'm here.

514
00:38:39,942 --> 00:38:42,236
I didn't do that on purpose, sorry.

515
00:38:42,320 --> 00:38:44,113
Oh, man.

516
00:38:45,197 --> 00:38:46,365
Mizusawa.

517
00:38:47,074 --> 00:38:48,200
That's you, right?

518
00:38:48,284 --> 00:38:50,786
What was the conclusion
on Aota's cause of death?

519
00:38:52,705 --> 00:38:54,707
It's believed to be tension pneumothorax

520
00:38:54,790 --> 00:38:56,917
resulting from a fall down the stairs.

521
00:38:57,001 --> 00:39:00,296
Is there a possibility that someone
intentionally pushed him down?

522
00:39:01,047 --> 00:39:04,133
None of the wounds
or bruises left on Mr. Aota's body

523
00:39:04,216 --> 00:39:06,969
provides clear proof of homicidal intent.

524
00:39:07,053 --> 00:39:10,306
Furthermore, considering their statements,
it doesn't add up.

525
00:39:11,015 --> 00:39:12,266
It doesn't add up, huh?

526
00:39:12,350 --> 00:39:13,434
Yes.

527
00:39:13,517 --> 00:39:14,560
It doesn't add up.

528
00:39:14,643 --> 00:39:19,106
It doesn't add up, which means
it was bribery after all.

529
00:39:19,190 --> 00:39:20,358
Oops.

530
00:39:20,441 --> 00:39:22,360
Tails, that makes sense.

531
00:39:22,443 --> 00:39:25,196
Excuse me, but who are you?

532
00:39:26,781 --> 00:39:27,948
I'm Ota.

533
00:39:28,532 --> 00:39:30,284
From the Public Prosecutors Office.

534
00:39:32,119 --> 00:39:33,496
A prosecutor?

535
00:39:33,579 --> 00:39:36,415
By the way,
I heard you went to see Dr. Kujo?

536
00:39:37,041 --> 00:39:38,042
How did it go?

537
00:39:38,125 --> 00:39:39,960
Were you able to speak with him?

538
00:39:43,297 --> 00:39:44,340
Well?

539
00:39:47,301 --> 00:39:48,636
You didn't?

540
00:39:48,719 --> 00:39:49,762
Oh, listen.

541
00:39:49,845 --> 00:39:54,850
Bribery paid in cash makes it
quite difficult to secure evidence.

542
00:39:55,768 --> 00:39:59,563
However, it has been confirmed
that Chairman Mukai

543
00:39:59,647 --> 00:40:01,273
was at the hotel that day.

544
00:40:01,816 --> 00:40:05,528
Therefore, if we have
Mr. Aota's autopsy results

545
00:40:06,487 --> 00:40:08,614
and the testimony of both individuals,

546
00:40:09,115 --> 00:40:12,535
it will serve as major leverage
to pursue Kakei.

547
00:40:12,618 --> 00:40:14,328
Your methods are foul.

548
00:40:15,246 --> 00:40:18,791
Our objective is also
to uncover the truth.

549
00:40:18,874 --> 00:40:21,752
An unnatural death
must always be autopsied.

550
00:40:21,836 --> 00:40:25,881
You just used the MEJ system
to bring down a powerful politician.

551
00:40:26,549 --> 00:40:27,383
Used?

552
00:40:27,466 --> 00:40:29,343
Fabricating a suicide by hanging

553
00:40:29,427 --> 00:40:32,138
constitutes the crimes
of damaging and abandoning a corpse.

554
00:40:34,473 --> 00:40:35,766
Is that so?

555
00:40:36,976 --> 00:40:38,060
What?

556
00:40:41,021 --> 00:40:42,314
Please leave.

557
00:40:45,276 --> 00:40:48,863
This is a place
to listen to the voices of the deceased

558
00:40:48,946 --> 00:40:51,282
and uncover the truth.

559
00:40:53,534 --> 00:40:58,205
It is a place to learn
what they loved and who loved them.

560
00:40:59,248 --> 00:41:01,917
It's not for you to bring in
your self-serving narratives!

561
00:41:19,518 --> 00:41:20,936
Didn't you hear her?

562
00:41:21,687 --> 00:41:22,855
Please leave.

563
00:41:30,321 --> 00:41:32,448
Heads or tails? Pick.

564
00:41:39,413 --> 00:41:40,414
What?

565
00:41:44,668 --> 00:41:47,421
See you around.

566
00:42:02,311 --> 00:42:04,855
I think I went a bit too far.

567
00:42:08,192 --> 00:42:10,903
You can just be scolded for it later.

568
00:42:12,321 --> 00:42:13,572
Don't worry about it.

569
00:42:46,272 --> 00:42:52,945
I still want… to live in a world
where I can call what is right, right.

570
00:42:55,239 --> 00:42:56,073
Yeah.

571
00:42:58,534 --> 00:43:01,287
You can't let people
you don't even believe are right

572
00:43:01,787 --> 00:43:03,831
run your life.

573
00:43:10,588 --> 00:43:12,464
Reading the room

574
00:43:13,132 --> 00:43:15,593
is different from
letting yourself be used.

575
00:43:20,723 --> 00:43:21,849
You're right.

576
00:43:31,317 --> 00:43:34,069
So Kakei ended up
not being prosecuted after all, huh?

577
00:43:34,737 --> 00:43:37,323
They say he claims
his secretary did everything.

578
00:43:38,407 --> 00:43:40,826
In the end, nothing changes, huh?

579
00:43:42,953 --> 00:43:44,913
It looks like the bill Mr. Aota drafted

580
00:43:46,081 --> 00:43:48,125
was properly submitted.

581
00:43:49,209 --> 00:43:51,837
The younger politicians
carried on his vision.

582
00:43:51,920 --> 00:43:53,339
It's true!

583
00:43:54,089 --> 00:43:56,425
If you seriously want to change things,

584
00:43:56,508 --> 00:43:57,968
they will change.

585
00:43:59,303 --> 00:44:01,096
I want to believe that.

586
00:44:05,392 --> 00:44:07,436
All right, let's work.

587
00:44:22,993 --> 00:44:25,871
Subtitle translation by: Maslin F.
